<div class="container">
    <h1>Understanding Classes in OOP</h1>
    <p>
        In Object-Oriented Programming, a <strong>class</strong> is like a <em>blueprint</em> or a <em>recipe</em>.  
        It defines what data (properties) and actions (methods) an object will have.  
        But remember: the class itself is just the plan — the actual things we create from it are called <strong>objects</strong>.
    </p>

    <h2>A Very Simple Class</h2>
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Example: Car Class</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
public class Car
{
    public string Brand;
    public string Color;
}
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>
    <p>
        👉 This class <code>Car</code> has two fields:  
        <ul>
            <li><code>Brand</code> → stores the car’s brand (like Toyota, BMW)</li>
            <li><code>Color</code> → stores the car’s color (like Red, Blue)</li>
        </ul>
        This is just a definition — it tells us that every car will have a brand and a color.
    </p>

    <h2>Adding Behavior with Methods</h2>
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Example: Calculator Class</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
public class Calculator
{
    public int Add(int a, int b)
    {
        return a + b;
    }
}
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>
    <p>
        👉 This <code>Calculator</code> class has a method <code>Add</code>:  
        <ul>
            <li>It takes two numbers as input.</li>
            <li>It returns the result of adding them.</li>
        </ul>
        Methods represent <strong>actions</strong> a class can perform.
    </p>

    <h2>Classes with Properties</h2>
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Example: Student Class</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
public class Student
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }

    public void Study()
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"{Name} is studying.");
    }
}
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>
    <p>
        👉 In this example:  
        <ul>
            <li><code>Id</code> and <code>Name</code> are <strong>properties</strong> (they store information).</li>
            <li><code>Study()</code> is a <strong>method</strong> (an action the student can perform).</li>
        </ul>
        Properties are commonly used in C# when defining classes because they allow controlled access to data.
    </p>

    <h2>Where Do We Use Classes?</h2>
    <p>
        Classes are used everywhere in real applications. For example, in an online shopping system you might have:
    </p>

        <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">Example: Product Class in E-Commerce</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-csharp">
public class Product
{
    public int Id { get; set; }
    public string Name { get; set; }
    public decimal Price { get; set; }

    public void DisplayInfo()
    {
        Console.WriteLine($"{Name} - ${Price}");
    }
}

// Using the class in a program:
Product laptop = new Product();
laptop.Id = 1;
laptop.Name = "Dell XPS 13";
laptop.Price = 999.99m;

laptop.DisplayInfo(); 
// Output: Dell XPS 13 - $999.99
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <p>
        👉 Let’s break down these important lines for beginners:
        <ul>
            <li><code>Product laptop = new Product();</code> → We are creating a new <strong>object</strong> of type <code>Product</code> and calling it <code>laptop</code>. Think of it as making one "real item" from the blueprint.</li>
            <li><code>laptop.Id = 1;</code> → We set the <strong>Id</strong> of this laptop to <code>1</code>. This is like giving it a unique number.</li>
            <li><code>laptop.Name = "Dell XPS 13";</code> → We set the <strong>Name</strong> property to a text value — here it’s the product’s name.</li>
            <li><code>laptop.Price = 999.99m;</code> → We give it a <strong>Price</strong>. The <code>m</code> at the end tells C# that this is a <em>decimal</em>, which is the correct type for money.</li>
        </ul>
        So together, these lines mean we created a laptop product with Id = 1, Name = "Dell XPS 13", and Price = $999.99.
    </p>


    <h2>Key Takeaways</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>A <strong>class</strong> is a <em>blueprint</em> for creating objects.</li>
        <li>Classes can contain <strong>fields</strong>, <strong>properties</strong>, and <strong>methods</strong>.</li>
        <li>By itself, a class does nothing — we use it to create <strong>objects</strong> in our programs.</li>
        <li>Real-world applications (like e-commerce, school systems, banking apps) are built with classes representing real entities.</li>
    </ul>

